1 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 14-102 of Title 43A, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. The purpose of the Oklahoma Elder Exploitation and Abuse Act
5 is to promote the general welfare of all citizens by establishing a
6 civil action for incapacitated persons and vulnerable adults which
7 provides for the protection of their rights and affords them a right
8 of civil action against those who neglect, exploit, or abuse them.
9 B. The purpose of the Oklahoma Elder Exploitation and Abuse Act
10 is to allow incapacitated persons and vulnerable adults, through
11 their legal representatives, to pursue claims against persons who
12 neglect, exploit, or abuse the incapacitated person or vulnerable
13 adult if he or she lacks the capacity to pursue such claims on his
14 or her own behalf.
15 C. The Oklahoma Elder Exploitation and Abuse Act does not
16 preclude an individual's mandatory responsibility to report to Adult
17 Protective Services or law enforcement if there is reasonable cause
18 to believe a vulnerable adult is being abused, neglected, or
19 exploited.
20 D. It is the intent of the Oklahoma Legislature:
21 1. That the district court shall exercise the authority
22 conferred by the Oklahoma Elder Exploitation and Abuse Act to
23 encourage the development of maximum self-reliance and independence
24 of incapacitated persons and vulnerable adults and make appointive
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1566 Page 2

1 and other orders only to the extent necessitated by the mental and
2 adaptive limitations of other conditions of the incapacitated or
3 partially incapacitated person warranting the action; and
4 2. That in performing their duties and exercising their powers,
5 legal representatives bringing claims under this act for
6 incapacitated persons and vulnerable adults shall:
7 a. assure, to the extent reasonably possible, that the
8 rights of the persons for whom they are appointed are
9 protected, and
10 b. encourage, to the extent reasonably possible,
11 incapacitated persons and vulnerable adults to
12 participate to the maximum extent of their abilities
13 in all decisions which affect them concerning the
14 claims afforded them under this act.
